stylometry: Production (or ordering) costs are costs that are incurred by a business producing or buying an item in an effort to sell the item and make a profit. However, holding costs are when a certain item sits in a warehouse as inventory and does not sell. The holding costs should not exceed what a company would make on an item, for example, if an item sits for too long then the profit the company would get on that item would go down because it sat for so long. The beauty of business is attempting to find the balance of how long an item should sit on the shelf before it becomes essentially worthless and you start loosing money. Inventory starts to sit when demand is low or if overproduction happens. This is when a company has to learn to balance holding costs with production costs and figuring how to maximize their profit by not over producing, under producing, and taking advantage of the market in a reasonable manner.
